Vietnam People 's Daily Network-Gulf Cooperation Council responds to common challenges Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman' s stopovers include Oman, United Arab Emirates(United Arab Emirates), Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait. Significantly, this is the first visit by Crown Prince Mohammed to Qatar since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed an embargo on Qatar in mid-2017, leading to the Gulf diplomatic crisis. In the crisis, Saudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain and Egypt severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and imposed a full embargo on it, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist organizations.Diplomatic tensions have seriously affected the internal unity of the GCC and negatively affected the economies of the countries in the region. Four Arab countries blocked land, sea and air routes to Qatar. The crisis was resolved only at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021.Saudi Arabia and Egypt are spearheading efforts to restore relations with Qatar by appointing new ambassadors from both countries in Qatar. The Gulf Arab states 'efforts to resolve their differences to restore relations with Qatar stem from the need to unite in the interests of all countries and regional stability in order to address common challenges. During the visit of the Saudi Crown Prince to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land route between the two Gulf neighbors. The 725-kilometer-long link will facilitate the travel of citizens and the integration of supply chains. Saudi Arabia Public Investment Fund(PIF) will invest $5 billion in Oman,The Saudi crown prince 's visit to the Gulf state coincided with a meeting between Iran and world powers to save the so-called Joint Comprehensive Plan of ActionThe Gulf Arab states have long viewed Iran as a long-term "competitor" and its nuclear program as a "threat" to regional security. the Gulf state believe that failure to resolve that Iran missile issue and take action to curb Iran's activities in the region is flawed. against the backdrop of the failure of major power to meet the aspirations of the Gulf states in their nuclear negotiations with Iran,Saudi Arabia has held direct talks with Iran. The goal is to contain the escalation of tensions in the region. This is one of the factors slowing economic growth in the GCC countries. The upcoming GCC summit will be the first of its kind since the end of a dispute between some member states and Qatar. This is an opportunity for the Gulf Cooperation Council to reassess the diplomatic achievements that have contributed to the restoration of GCC unity and to propose measures to enable its member States to cooperate fully in addressing common challenges and contributing to the stability and development of the Gulf States.
